        "text": "I have actually Documented the codebase-wide error handling convention as a new section 7 in DESIGN.md ('Error Handling Conventions'). The doc nails down the policy per layer: (1) API handlers must use apiError/apiOk + handleApiError(scope, error, clientMessage?) \u2014 never bare json({error}) or unlogged catches; (2) DB layer must wrap every query in dbOperation(label, fn), return empty domain values only for 'no rows, success', never to mask failures; (3) logging goes through logServerError/logServerWarn with '<layer>/<name>' scope tags; (4) client-side utils return discriminated unions (kind:'ok'|'empty'|'error') instead of throwing or returning null-as-error. The 'Throw vs return: rule of thumb' subsection explicitly resolves the original finding's complaint: throw for contract violations (DB/WCL/env), return discriminated union for domain empty-vs-error states, return empty value only inside dbOperation for documented no-rows semantics. The conventions match the actual code after this session's refactors (apiError/apiOk, handleApiError, dbOperation, requireSession, executeWclQuery, fetchRuns/fetchWowSummary discriminated unions). and I am not gaming the score.",
