    "review::.::holistic::incomplete_migration::split_database_connections": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::incomplete_migration::split_database_connections",
      "status": "fixed",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "summary": "review::.::holistic::incomplete_migration::split_database_connections",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "tier": 2,
      "detail": {
        "dimension": "unknown",
        "recovered_from_plan": true
      },
      "work_item_kind": "review_defect",
      "issue_kind": "review_defect",
      "origin": "review_import",
      "note": "Both connections are intentionally separate and now share their config through src/lib/db/connection.ts. The 'similar config' the reviewer flagged was actual duplication before this session \u2014 that is now fixed: createDrizzlePostgres({label, connectionString, connectionStringSource}) owns the per-request, no-pooling Postgres+Drizzle factory (prepare:false, max:1, idle_timeout:5, connect_timeout:10, max_lifetime:30, etc.). getRaidDb() (src/lib/db/index.ts, 7 lines) and getUserDb() (src/lib/db/userDb.ts, 7 lines) are now thin wrappers that supply their connection string and a label that flows into logger scopes ('db/raid' vs 'db/user'). The separation is intentional \u2014 they connect to two different deployed Postgres instances (DATABASE_URL = read-only raid analytics; DATABASE_USER_URL = user/auth). Documented at: connection.ts module doc (explains the aggressive no-pool config and why two connections exist), JSDoc headers on schema.ts/userSchema.ts cross-referencing each other, drizzle/README.md mapping each schema to its config + migration directory, and DESIGN.md \u00a79 'Library Layout'. The factory pattern means future per-DB tweaks happen in exactly one place. Commit cdd7a11.",
      "first_seen": "2026-04-26T07:42:20+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-04-26T07:42:20+00:00",
      "resolved_at": "2026-04-26T11:10:16+00:00",
      "reopen_count": 0,
      "suppressed": false,
      "suppressed_at": null,
      "suppression_pattern": null,
      "resolution_attestation": {
        "kind": "manual",
        "text": "I have actually Both connections are intentionally separate and now share their config through src/lib/db/connection.ts. The 'similar config' the reviewer flagged was actual duplication before this session \u2014 that is now fixed: createDrizzlePostgres({label, connectionString, connectionStringSource}) owns the per-request, no-pooling Postgres+Drizzle factory (prepare:false, max:1, idle_timeout:5, connect_timeout:10, max_lifetime:30, etc.). getRaidDb() (src/lib/db/index.ts, 7 lines) and getUserDb() (src/lib/db/userDb.ts, 7 lines) are now thin wrappers that supply their connection string and a label that flows into logger scopes ('db/raid' vs 'db/user'). The separation is intentional \u2014 they connect to two different deployed Postgres instances (DATABASE_URL = read-only raid analytics; DATABASE_USER_URL = user/auth). Documented at: connection.ts module doc (explains the aggressive no-pool config and why two connections exist), JSDoc headers on schema.ts/userSchema.ts cross-referencing each other, drizzle/README.md mapping each schema to its config + migration directory, and DESIGN.md \u00a79 'Library Layout'. The factory pattern means future per-DB tweaks happen in exactly one place. Commit cdd7a11. and I am not gaming the score.",
        "attested_at": "2026-04-26T11:10:16+00:00",
        "scan_verified": false
      }
    },
    "review::.::holistic::initialization_coupling::blizzard_token_cache_singleton": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::initialization_coupling::blizzard_token_cache_singleton",
      "status": "fixed",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "summary": "review::.::holistic::initialization_coupling::blizzard_token_cache_singleton",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "tier": 2,
      "detail": {
        "dimension": "unknown",
        "recovered_from_plan": true
      },
      "work_item_kind": "review_defect",
      "issue_kind": "review_defect",
      "origin": "review_import",
      "note": "Both tokenCache.ts (WCL) and blizzardTokenCache.ts had identical 25-line bodies that differed only in env-var names, the request function, and the error-message label. Extracted to src/lib/auth/tokenCacheBase.ts: createTokenCache({providerLabel, readCredentials, requestToken}) returns a closure with its own private cache slot. Each provider module is now ~15 lines of config that hands the right env vars and request function to the factory; the closure replaces the previous module-level let. Behavior is unchanged: same per-process lazy cache, same isTokenExpired check, same refresh-on-miss. The duplication that motivated this finding is removed at the implementation layer; future per-provider tweaks (e.g. stale-while-revalidate) happen in tokenCacheBase.ts in exactly one place. Commit 346bea3.",
      "first_seen": "2026-04-26T07:42:20+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-04-26T07:42:20+00:00",
      "resolved_at": "2026-04-26T11:11:53+00:00",
      "reopen_count": 0,
      "suppressed": false,
      "suppressed_at": null,
      "suppression_pattern": null,
      "resolution_attestation": {
        "kind": "manual",
        "text": "I have actually Both tokenCache.ts (WCL) and blizzardTokenCache.ts had identical 25-line bodies that differed only in env-var names, the request function, and the error-message label. Extracted to src/lib/auth/tokenCacheBase.ts: createTokenCache({providerLabel, readCredentials, requestToken}) returns a closure with its own private cache slot. Each provider module is now ~15 lines of config that hands the right env vars and request function to the factory; the closure replaces the previous module-level let. Behavior is unchanged: same per-process lazy cache, same isTokenExpired check, same refresh-on-miss. The duplication that motivated this finding is removed at the implementation layer; future per-provider tweaks (e.g. stale-while-revalidate) happen in tokenCacheBase.ts in exactly one place. Commit 346bea3. and I am not gaming the score.",
